Soybean protein naturally contains compounds called isoflavones, predominantly genistein and daidzein. These compounds are not estrogens and do not directly add to estrogen levels in the blood. They can, however, affect estrogen metabolism.

A study published in the March 2005 issue of "The Journal of Nutrition" investigated the effects of soy protein and isoflavones on blood estrogen levels in 35 healthy men, average age 28. After 2 months, men consuming diets containing soy protein rich in isoflavones had blood estrogen levels slightly higher than men consuming milk protein, although the increase was not statistically significant. However, men eating soy protein with most of the isoflavones removed had significantly higher estrogen levels than men eating milk protein. The researchers conducting this small study concluded that these effects were "minor."

Dairy contains actual mammalian estrogen, which is completely recognized as a hormone by your body since you're also a mammal, and has been shown to cause gyno and other hormonal imbalances in men. Soy, on the other hand, is made of phytoestrogens which are far far less potent than real estrogen. You would need to eat 16 servings of soy a day in order to actually get feminizing hormone effects from the phytoestrogens. A far more potent source of phytoestrogens is beer, which contains 300x more than soy. If you are so scared of the hormonal effects from phytoestrogens, STOP DRINKING BEER and DAIRY then, it's hurting you way more than soy!

Like with most hormones, it's not about adverse affects on adult individuals. It's about how it affects the developing mind and body, primarily during puberty. There are real reasons for concern with xenoestrogens and sex hormones and indeed with any products which may contain them. And yes, xenoestrogens can in fact have adverse effects on the body, it doesn't have to be the actual exact hormone, this is why for example drugs and caffeine can achieve the effects in your body that normally only occur from chemicals made in the body, because they fit into the synapse receptors. The concept of xenohormones affecting you adversely is not a new one, it's a well known thing.

The decrease of sperm count and quality in males in civilized countries is also not a myth at all as shown in a recent study, and is actually quite a bit more serious than you might think. The exact cause isn't yet determined but It is thought to have to do with xenoestrogens in microplastics, or with birth control residue flushed down the drain which later enters the water supply as it's incredibly hard to filter out completely, or a mix of the two. 

Given that there's been such a massive reduction in these, it's not exactly impossible that something such as soy could affect you during development, especially if you take into account the large difference between asians and europeans in stature, muscle, etc, the former of which historically consumes massive quantities of soy. 
(Even though comparing asians to europeans isn't exactly reliable as there are massive genetic differences.)

Bottom line: Don't dismiss an actual possible problem just because it's also an overused meme.
